giveness in Communities Affected by Deracination in Colombia -- tThe Subaltern Can Speak: The Mobility Strategies of Forced Migrants in Kenya’s Kalobeyei Integrated Settlement -- tConclusion: Postcoloniality and Forced Migration -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis powerful book explicates the many ways in which colonial encounters continue to shape forced migration, ever evolving with times and various geographical contexts. Bringing historians, political scientists, sociologists, anthropologists and criminologists together, the book presents examples of forced migration events and politics ranging from the 18th century to the practices and geopolitics of the present day. These case studies, covering Europe, Africa, North America, Asia and South America, are then put in dialogue with each other to propose new theoretical and real-world agendas for the field. As the pervasive legacies of colonialism continue to shape global politics, this unprecedented book moves beyond critique, ahistoricity and Eurocentrism in refugee and forced migration studies and establishes postcoloniality and forced migration as an important field of migration research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aForced migrationxHistory. 0aPostcolonialism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAdderley, Laura Rosanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoeyink, Clayton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChowdhory, Nasreen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwert, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFett, Sharla M., econtributor.4